The overall structure of my project

NetworkRoutingSimulator/
│
├── cpp_backend/
│   ├── graph.cpp
│   ├── graph.h
│   ├── routing.cpp
│   ├── routing.h
│   ├── main.cpp              
│   ├── Makefile              
│
├── python_frontend/
│   ├── main.py              
│   ├── controller.py         # Communicates with C++ backend
│   ├── visualize.py          # Graph visualization (using networkx/matplotlib)
│   ├── data/
│   │   ├── sample_network.txt
│   │   └── results.json
│
└── README.md         




***************I’ll split the project into two main layers:*****************

"""""""""""""""""""""a. Backend (C++)"""""""""""""""""""""""
Handles:

1)Heavy data structure work
2)Routing algorithms (Dijkstra, Bellman-Ford, etc.)
3)Graph creation and path calculations
4)C++ gives faster execution, especially for large networks or complex routing.

"""""""""""""""""""""b. Frontend / Control (Python)"""""""""""""""""""
Handles:
1)ser interface (CLI or GUI using Tkinter/PyQt/Streamlit)
2)Input/output management
3)Visualization of network routes
4)Sending data to C++ and reading back results
